<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-arc-length">
  <title>Arc length</title>

  <objectives>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Measure the length of a curve by accumulating tiny distance increments along its path.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Relate arc length to how quickly the coordinates change along the curve.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Interpret arc length as the total distance traveled by a moving particle.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </objectives>
  
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Introduction goes here.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <p>
        Differential of arc length:
        <me>
          \dd s=\sqrt{(\dd{x})^{2}+(\dd{y})^{2}}
        </me>
        (Show right triangle diagram)
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Arc length:
        <me>
          s=\int_{a}^{b}\dd{s}=\int_{a}^{b}\sqrt{\qty(\dv{x}{t})^{2}+\qty(\dv{y}{t})^{2}}\dd{t}
        </me>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        If the curve is a function <m>y=f(x)</m>, the formula simplifies:
        <me>
          s=\int_{a}^{b} \sqrt{1+f'(x)^{2}}\dd{x}
        </me>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Easy to find arc length of a circle, but not doable for an ellipse! More on that later.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        If <m>(x,y)</m> is considered as the position of a particle, then the arc length is the distance traveled.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Polar arc length:
        <me>
          s=\int_{\alpha}^{\beta} \sqrt{r^{2}+\qty(\dv{r}{\theta})^{2}}\dd{\theta}
        </me>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
        <p>
            Why is the inverse of the sine function called the ARCsine function? Because it gives the angle whose sine is a given number, and the <q>arc</q> refers to the arc length of the unit circle corresponding to that angle.
        </p>
    </li>

    <li>
        <p>
            Fix <m>r=1</m>, so <m>x=\cos\theta</m>, <m>y=\sin\theta</m>, and <m>m=\tan\theta</m>. Then we can express the inverse trigonometric functions in terms of these variables:
            <me>
                \theta = \arcsin y = \arccos x = \arctan m
            </me>
        </p>
    </li>

    <li>
        <p>
            The derivatives of the inverse trigonometric functions can be found using implicit differentiation. For example, if <m>\theta=\arcsin y</m>, then we have <m>\sin \theta = y</m>. Differentiating both sides with respect to <m>x</m> gives:
            <me>
                \cos \theta \cdot \dv{\theta}{y} = 1
            </me>
            Solving for <m>\DS\dv{\theta}{y}</m> yields:
            <me>
                \dv{\theta}{y} = \frac{1}{\cos \theta} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{1-y^2}}
            </me>
        </p>
    </li>

    <li>
        <p>
            Similarly, for <m>\theta=\arccos x</m>, we have <m>\cos \theta = x</m>. Differentiating both sides gives:
            <me>
                -\sin \theta \cdot \dv{\theta}{x} = 1
            </me>
            Solving for <m>\DS\dv{\theta}{x}</m> yields:
            <me>
                \dv{\theta}{x} = -\frac{1}{\sin \theta} = -\frac{1}{\sqrt{1-x^2}}
            </me>
        </p>
    </li>

    <li>
        <p>
            For <m>\theta=\arctan m</m>, we have <m>\tan \theta = m</m>. Differentiating both sides gives:
            <me>
                \sec^2 \theta \cdot \dv{\theta}{m} = 1
            </me>
            Solving for <m>\DS\dv{\theta}{m}</m> yields:
            <me>
                \dv{\theta}{m} = \frac{1}{\sec^2 \theta} = \frac{1}{1+m^2}
            </me>
        </p>
    </li>

    <li>
        <p>
            Put another way, the derivatives of <m>\arcsin</m>, <m>\arccos</m>, and <m>\arctan</m> can be thought of as <m>\DS\dv{\theta}{y}</m>, <m>\DS\dv{\theta}{x}</m>, and <m>\DS\dv{\theta}{m}</m> respectively, where <m>\theta</m> is the angle corresponding to the given trigonometric value.
        </p>
    </li>

    <li>
        <p>
            Using <m>x</m> as a generic independent variable, we can express the derivatives of the inverse trigonometric functions in terms of <m>x</m>:
            <md>
                <mrow>\dv{x}\arcsin x \amp = \frac{1}{\sqrt{1-x^2}}</mrow>
                <mrow>\dv{x}\arccos x \amp = -\frac{1}{\sqrt{1-x^2}}</mrow>
                <mrow>\dv{x}\arctan x \amp = \frac{1}{1+x^2}</mrow>
            </md>
        </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
  
</section>
